07569nam a22010095i 9781783098552DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017enk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817830985527 a10.21832/97817830985522doi  a(DE-B1597)491477  a(OCoLC)1001364371  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST 7aLAN0200002bisacsh00aGoing Performative in Intercultural Education :bInternational Contexts, Theoretical Perspectives and Models of Practice /ced. by John Crutchfield, Manfred Schewe. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguages for Intercultural Communication and Education00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction: Going Performative in Intercultural Education: International Contexts – Theoretical Perspectives – Models of Practice -- tPart 1: First Impressions -- t1. The Intercultural Surprise: Teaching Improvisational Theatre in Different Cultural Contexts -- tPart 2: Focus on Schools (Immigrant/Refugee Children) -- t2. The Ethics of Performative Approaches in Intercultural Education -- t3. Diadrasis: An Interactive Project on Language Teaching to Immigrant Families in a Greek School -- t4. Developing Empathy Through Theatre: A Transcultural Perspective in Second Language Education -- tPart 3: Focus on Teacher Training -- t5. Interculturality in Foreign Language Teacher Training: Performing Arts Projects Across National, Language and Cultural Borders -- t6. Exploring Diversity Through Drama Education: English– Turkish Perspectives on National German Stereotypes in Foreign Language Teacher Training -- t7. Staging Otherness: Three New Empirical Studies in Dramapädagogik with Relevance for Intercultural Learning in the Foreign Language Classroom -- tPart 4: Focus on Specific Performative Approaches: Process Drama and Playback Theatre -- t8. Using Process Drama to Engage Beginner Learners in Intercultural Language Learning -- t9. Intercultural/Dramatic Tension and the Nature of Intercultural Engagement -- tPart 5: Focus on Performance and Biography -- t10. Enacting Life: Dialogue and Mediation in Cross-Cultural Contexts -- t11. Suitcase of Survival: Performance, Biography and Intercultural Education -- tPart 6: Performative Approaches to Intercultural Education: A Culture-Specific Perspective -- t12. The Intercultural Journey: Drama-Based Practitioners in JFL in North America, and in JSL and EFL in Japan -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the last two decades drama pedagogy has helped to lay the foundations for a new teaching and learning culture, one that accentuates physicality and centres on performative experience. Signs of this ‘performative turn’ in education are especially strong in the field of foreign/second language teaching. This volume introduces scholars, language teachers, student teachers and drama practitioners to the concept of a performative foreign language didactics. Approaching the subject from a wide variety of contexts, the contributors explore the extent to which performative approaches, emphasising the role of the body as a learning medium, can achieve deep intercultural learning. Drama activities such as improvisation, hot seating and tableaux are shown to create rich opportunities for intercultural encounters that transport students beyond the parameters of conventional language, literature and culture education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDrama in education. 0aEducation, Bilingual. 0aMulticultural educationxActivity programs. 0aMulticultural education. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  adrama in education.  adrama ped